{
  "jipipe:project-type" : "project",
  "jipipe:project-format-version" : 1,
  "metadata" : {
    "name" : "Example: Loading and processing an image",
    "description" : "<html>\n  <head>\n    \n  </head>\n  <body>\n    <h1>\n      Example: Loading and processing an image\n    </h1>\n    <p>\n      JIPipe organizes pipelines in projects that can be saved and loaded from \n      disk. Each pipeline is organized into <b>Compartments</b> that separate \n      the whole graph into functional units. You can find an overview of all \n      compartments in the <i>Compartments</i> tab. You can re-open the tab by \n      selecting <i>Compartment &gt; Edit compartments</i> if you closed the \n      tab.<br><br>By double-clicking a compartment in the overview, JIPipe \n      will open an editor where you can modify the sub-pipeline that is \n      associated to the compartment. If you just want to run a project, you \n      can find the `Run` button at the top-right corner. Pipeline developers \n      might have organized a set of most common pipeline parameters. You can \n      find them in <i>Project &gt; Project overview</i> alongside additional \n      information like the authors, citations, and website. This template \n      contains one graph node called 'Analysis'\n    </p>\n    <p>\n      \n    </p>\n    <p>\n      This project shows how to load an segment multiple folders containing \n      TIFF files and visualize the resulting ROI.\n    </p>\n  </body>\n</html>\n",
    "authors" : [ ],
    "acknowledgements" : [ ],
    "website" : "",
    "license" : "",
    "citation" : "",
    "update-site-dependencies" : [ ],
